{meta: title If I Never Have Anything Else}
{meta: artist Ernest Tubb}
{meta: composer Vic McAlpin and Ernest Tubb}

{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[G]It would be nice if I could buy you almost [D7]anything
[G]It would be nice to have more diamonds for your weddin’ ring
[D7]But my love is all I have I can’t offer the rest
[G]But I’ll always have dreams if I never have anything else
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
[D7]Some men can offer silver and gold
[G]But I’ve heard it said that money grows cold
[D7]But my love will be true I can’t offer the rest
[G]But I’ll always have dreams if I never have anything else
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 3}
[D7]It would be nice to own a mansion and a car or two
[G]It would be nice to own just about anything new
[D7]But my love is all I have I can’t offer the rest
[G]But I’ll always have dreams if I never have anything else
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
[D7]Some men can offer silver and gold
[G]But I’ve heard it said that money grows cold
[D7]But my love will be true and it’s yours to possess
[G]And I’ll always have dreams if I never have anything else
{end_of_verse}
